video_title: Atheist vs Christian vs Spiritual Thinker: The Paperclip Problem That Exposes Religion!
comment_text:
The atheist presented interesting philosophical ideas and explanations. “Do I know my own purpose…assumes there is a purpose to know,” and “We’ve eliminated the daily survival need which has led to this [existential] crisis” of what do we do now. Theism, or anything else, bringing positive meaning (or detriment) to an individual does not mean that it is truth. His ideas on consciousness were very interesting. 

What the “spiritual” psychiatrist describes, (over and over yikes) as “quantifiable,” that specific action having a neurobiological effect leading to feeling less depressed and finding meaning…is essentially therapy. Yes, therapy can shift your mental/physical state, and it’s lovely that he helps people, but that doesn’t answer any existential questions about why people cannot find purpose, and is that universal.

I think that Stephen presented some great examples with friends who were both feeling down. None of the guests truly answered these questions and yet they each thought that they did. 

The Christian said that meaning will be found in religion and belief in higher power. 
The psychiatrist said that meaning is found in both a higher power and after a person does therapeutic work that affects their brain. 
The atheist says that meaning was evolutionarily diminished, and this is why we are feel aimless and lost, and anything else is subjective thought, and not necessarily truth. 

I think it was absolutely brilliant to bring all three of these different viewpoints together. Even if most of it was not fascinating, all are worth hearing. Of course we can feel better with belief in a higher power, like the friend in Dubai, because then we are connected to something greater than ourselves. (Though it was still shocking to hear a person state that the subjective feeling was “evidence” of truth. Erm, no.) Of course we can find meaning and purpose by changing our neurobiological chemistry through therapeutic action, but we also need to understand our own existence when we are intellectual. Of course we will have more time to ponder why we are here and what we should be doing when we are no longer being chased by Sabre tooth cats. I believe that this evolutionary understanding is what benefits me the most. Then they can choose to integrate therapy, spirituality, etc. Each of these viewpoints expressed are relevant to someone. 

Humans are complex, social beings with the leisure to think about their own existence. I think about my childhood and how everything was about joy in the moment, playing was paramount, and how life through my limited ancillary lens resulted in a less complicated world. As children we also are never alone at the start, nearly always spending time with other people. 

Now we are all more and more separated via technology. We spend too much time alone, in our own technology bubble. We compare ourselves to others in ways that never existed throughout history, which can lead to feeling inadequate and unfulfilled. People are struggling and suffering all over the world, which we are acutely aware of…and evil, for lack of a better word, conflict, impending doom, destruction of the planet, and acute fear are pervasive and normalized, extinguishing childhood ideals. 

It’s not all that complicated that existence in a modern world has lead to humans becoming more complex. We have all the information, yet there is no single answer.
author: @TessaLeigh

comment_text: I find this an interesting discussion, but feel the premise is a bit off.  First, it would have been lovely to have included a feminine voice in the discussion.  This conversation definitely had a masculine skew, IMO. People often find purpose and meaning being on any side of a religious or spiritual position. Consider the possibility that there can be a hierarchy of meaning and purpose. Theories of developmental psychology and pediatrics often focus on purpose early in life.  As we mature we replace that purpose with learning to set appropriate goals and achievements. If we continue in that maturation we develop a deeper inner awareness that reveals a correspondingly deeper and richer sense of purpose. Modern technology with social media and gaming hacks the dopamine reward system and highjacks our evolution of purpose and reduces the lives of some people to that ascribed by the social media or games.

comment_text: 1:19:00 I think the key thing Alex misses here is the direct experience of doing something for the sake of it, and being happy. If you have such an experience, you don't have to imagine sisyphus being happy, you can understand how and why he is, eventhough he is doing something meaningless. I can explain this with the analogy of colour, if you were to talk to a blind person and describe to him what colour looks like, he wouldn't truly understand. He can only imagine what colour would like, but if his blindness were to be cured and he sees colour for the first time, he would understand it, and he would realise that the imaginations he created previously were completely off the mark. And people who do see colour would not call it a delusion, it might be, but two people can sit together and acknowledge colours when they see it, it's a shared direct experience that they can communicate. Same with an ego death, if you can experience what it's like to do something for the sake of it, and derive joy out of it, you get why sisyphus can be happy, you don't have to imagine it, and you wouldn't call it a delusion just like seeing colour isn't a delusion. Maybe it is in an absolute, capital T Truth sense, but when it comes to giving people meaning, that doesn't matter because we understand the mechanism with which it can be achieved, so it is true to us. We may never understand Truth, we do not have the perspective for it, but what can be true for us, and for others, like seeing colour matters more, and is ultimately more useful in life.

video_title: Atheist vs Christian vs Spiritual Thinker: The Paperclip Problem That Exposes Religion!
comment_text:
From a young age, many of us are taught a familiar narrative about what life should look like: go to school, get a good job, buy a house, build a family, and eventually retire to enjoy the fruits of your labour. It's a formula that's been passed down through generations—structured, linear, and, for a time, widely attainable.

But in today’s world, that blueprint feels increasingly out of reach for many. Economic instability, skyrocketing living costs, shifting job markets, and the pressures of modern life have made what was once considered a standard path far less accessible. Even more, many are beginning to question whether that path was ever truly fulfilling in the first place—or if it was simply a social expectation dressed up as purpose.

The truth is, not everyone fits into that mold. Some realise early on that their aspirations lie elsewhere. For others, the realisation comes later, often after chasing the traditional path and finding it empty or unattainable. As the old narrative begins to unravel, a deeper question emerges: If not that, then what?

In the absence of a clear, universal road map, people begin to search for meaning and purpose elsewhere. For some, it’s in spirituality or religion—finding solace and direction in faith. For others, it’s through physical pursuits like fitness or athleticism, where the body becomes a vessel for discipline and transformation. Some turn to creativity—art, music, writing—as a way to express their inner worlds. Others dive into nature, activism, community, entrepreneurship, or personal growth.

The point is, the search for meaning doesn’t follow a single path. It’s personal. And in a world where the traditional markers of success are no longer guaranteed—or even desirable for some—this search becomes more important than ever.

What we’re seeing is not a loss of direction, but a shift. A shift from living by default to living with intention. From chasing what we’re told we should want, to discovering what truly matters to us.

Meaning isn’t something you’re handed—it’s something you create. And purpose isn’t always found in achieving a big, bold goal; sometimes it’s in the quiet commitment to living authentically, staying curious, helping others, or simply being present.

In my opinion, God is a coping mechanism that is too obvious to fall back on to search for a purpose that is not a true meaning and is told to you to believe not to find it yourself. comment_text:
You really hit the mark here, man. Perfectly said. I think that Alex is just too used to being in "debate mode" that he just has it on in every discussion, even though its not needed at times. What he's maybe missing is that humans, or at least most humans, are not rational creatures. Our feelings often override our logic. 

And so, is it really necessary to definitively assert that we only need logical answers and solutions? I mean, ideally, yes maybe thats good. But it can only work if it we live in an idealistic utopia where the best answers can be universally taught to and understood by everyone, and everyone has the same intellectual capacity and environment to be able to accept it.

I find that in the end, best solutions always comes in spectrums and variations. Alex is on the left while Greg's on the right. And Dr K is the one who's aware of this spectrum and is more practical with his approach. Different people have different methods of living with the world.


But then, I see Alex's point. I dont think we'll evolve much as a species until we grow out of these "coping mechanisms". Because we saw what happens when world powers were motivated by these claims of objective truths (which is greg's side). 

In the end, I think Dr K's position is the most practically beneficial in finding a sense of purpose.  Maybe the difference lies in how these people value different facets of experience. Dr K sees value in subjectivity, while alex and greg only cares about what is objective.

comment_text:
It’s striking that humanity keeps circling back to the same questions: Why am I here? What’s my purpose? Why is there so much suffering? Every culture, every generation wrestles with them. And yet, the Bible has been addressing these very questions from the beginning — not with abstract philosophy, but with a consistent story of God’s purpose for mankind.

From the start, God’s purpose was clear: He created humans in His image, to live forever on a perfect earth, caring for creation and enjoying a close relationship with Him (Genesis 1:26-28). That was the meaning and destiny He set before us. When Adam and Eve chose independence, it wasn’t just about eating fruit — it was a rebellion against God’s right to rule. At that moment, a question was raised that has shaped history ever since: Can humans find meaning and success apart from God?

This explains why God didn’t just “start over.” If He had, the issue would have remained unresolved, and rebellion could rise again. Instead, He allowed time to pass so the evidence could mount: that humans, no matter how advanced, cannot bring peace, justice, or lasting happiness without Him (Jeremiah 10:23). Meanwhile, the Bible tells us the real ruler of this world is not God, but Satan — “the god of this world” (2 Corinthians 4:4) — who has twisted truth, fueled suffering, and spread despair. That explains the state of the world far better than the idea of a cold, absent Creator.

But here’s where hope shines through: God’s plan never changed. He promised a Messiah who would undo the damage of Adam’s choice. Through Jesus’ death and resurrection, the way back to friendship with God was opened (Romans 5:18-19). Jesus taught us to pray for God’s Kingdom to come — not for us to escape earth, but for His rule to be restored here, “on earth as it is in heaven” (Matthew 6:10).

This Kingdom is the heart of the Bible’s hope. A limited number will share with Christ in heaven, but the vast majority of faithful humans will live forever on a restored earth (Psalm 37:29; Revelation 21:3-5). No more cancer, war, or injustice. Just life as it was always meant to be — meaningful, secure, and everlasting.

That longing people feel — for meaning, for justice, for permanence — is not random. Ecclesiastes says God “put eternity in our hearts” (Ecclesiastes 3:11). It’s a built-in hunger for what only He can give. Philosophers can debate subjective vs. objective meaning, but the Bible gives both: objective purpose from our Creator, and subjective fulfillment when we live in harmony with that purpose.

So why does God still wait? Because He is giving every person the chance to hear this good news and decide where they stand (2 Peter 3:9). When the time comes, He will replace human governments with His Kingdom (Daniel 2:44), and the question of who should rule will be settled forever.

That’s the real story of humanity: not meaningless suffering, not an arbitrary purpose, but a patient God working out His plan to restore us to the life we were created for. And that’s why the Bible is not just another philosophy, but the greatest message of hope humanity has ever been given.

comment_text:
That’s one of the deepest questions humans have asked for thousands of years, and the answer really depends on perspective:

1. Philosophical Views

Existentialism (Sartre, Camus): Life has no built-in purpose; we create our own meaning through choices and actions.

Humanism: Meaning comes from relationships, growth, knowledge, and contributing to others.

Stoicism: Life’s purpose is to live in harmony with nature, cultivate virtue, and accept what we cannot control.


2. Religious/Spiritual Views

Christianity/Islam/Judaism: Life’s purpose is to serve, worship, and live according to God’s will, preparing for eternal life.

Hinduism/Buddhism: Life is part of a cycle (samsara); the purpose is spiritual growth and liberation (moksha, nirvana).

Other spiritual traditions: Life can be seen as a journey of the soul, learning lessons, and evolving.


3. Scientific/Evolutionary View

From biology: the "purpose" of life is survival, reproduction, and passing on genes.

From science/philosophy: humans, with consciousness, can go beyond survival and invent meaning.


4. Personal/Practical View

Meaning often comes from love, family, creativity, growth, service, adventure, and legacy.

Some find it in wealth, power, or achievement; others in peace, wisdom, and compassion.


👉 In short: Life doesn’t come with a single universal purpose. Instead, you give it meaning through what you value most.

comment_text:
God Is Love

I know this may sound unreasonable, but it unfolds when you open your heart, mind, and soul.

Many people wrestle with their own perception of God  sometimes even rejecting the very image they hold. Yet, through the lens of any religion, these are often the same people you’d call faithful and righteous.

“God is love.” Just three simple words, yet they carry all the attributes of who He is. You can reject, abandon, or disagree, but deep within every human being there is a light  a quiet, glittering pull toward goodness. We do good not only because of ethics or social expectations, but because God’s nature lives within us.

When God said, “Let us make man in our own image,” He placed His imprint on us. As His image-bearers, we have free will the ability to choose what to believe and what to walk away from. But nothing can erase that inner spark.

May these words be a blessing to anyone who reads them, and may you encounter God’s nature in the deepest parts of your own being.

Love is not just a feeling. Feelings are temporary, they rise and fall. Love is action — consistent, intentional, and sometimes costly action.

Purpose isn’t something you stumble upon--it’s something you build. Start by putting your own house in order:
* Earn enough to live with dignity.
* Take care of your health.
* Spend real time with your family and the people who matter.
          Once your foundation is solid, lift your eyes outward. Look at the problems standing in the way of the common good. Choose one that stirs you. Learn about it deeply--so deeply that you understand the roots, not just the headlines.
Then act. Small or big, it doesn’t matter, as long as it’s real. Along the way, gather people who share your values. Community is the soil where purpose grows.
Do this, and life stops being something you’re just surviving. It becomes something you’re enriching--for yourself and for others.

video_title: Atheist vs Christian vs Spiritual Thinker: The Paperclip Problem That Exposes Religion!
comment_text:
🙃"If all of us and everything are part of something larger – a consciousness, a source, God, some idea that connects everything – then the question arises: if that consciousness has the attributes of “omni” (omnipresent, omnipotent, omniscient), why create something limited?
Maybe to feel what is known but not felt – especially those limits that contradict its nature.

The difference is simple: to know is a concept; to experience is the taste and weight of the moment. That is why the meaning of creating limitations is not about gaining information – it is about living the form of the experience.

If we consider omnipresence outside of time and accept that everything happens together, then human experience of the world may be both effect and cause. What if everything that takes place is simultaneously necessary for it to take place? The attributes of “omni” do not exclude elements of reality – they co-create themselves in everything that exists. As David R. Hawkins put it: “Observer, Creator and Knower blur and become, to an equal degree, result and process.” We have lived this through generations (humans, and perhaps more), joining in consciousness and becoming, in a sense, a “god” to ourselves – creating one another.
Consciousness is like an orchestra; individuals – instruments, playing their melodies, inspiring one another in a jazz improvisation of an endless symphony.

If the purpose of human life is experience and self-improvement – as many philosophers wrote, and as Epictetus says: “There is only one thing for which God has sent me into the world, and that is to develop every kind of virtue or strength, and there is nothing in all the world that I cannot use for this purpose.” – then isn’t the desire for experience at the root of our everyday difficulties?
Whether true or not, isn't it a beautiful way to live?

When we compare ourselves to others, when we think about what we don’t have, what we didn’t do, what we haven’t achieved – aren’t our urges and desires essentially demands for experiences? We always want what we lack; we want more, we want different — and all the more so the more we see it in others. How much of this is curiosity – the wish to check, “what would it be like”? What would happen? What would become possible?

Why then do desires seem to focus on pleasure?
Is that really so? Are there pleasures that do not carry difficulty, effort, or negative consequences? Or maybe some of our actions aim at harder, even shattering experiences – only the awareness of their intention is hidden, veiled by the ego, because otherwise the perception of the experience would change? After all, attitude, expectations and comparison shape and color the pleasure or displeasure of the experience.

So perhaps, subconsciously (or supraconsciously), we seek the full spectrum of experiences to gather perspective and grow. How many times have you seen behavior that looked self-destructive from the outside, but from the participant’s view made developmental sense? How much changes when you are inside – fully, directly experiencing – versus looking from the distance?

If our goal is to draw conclusions and transform, then perhaps the difficulty of drawing conclusions is also part of that process. That difficulty itself may be a necessary experience – a missing element of that all-knowing consciousness. When there are no limits and everything goes “perfectly,” who do we become then? What do we live through and what conclusions can we draw? If everything is simple, what is its value? Where is transformation, where is refinement, if you are already perfect?

This is not about seeking suffering for its own sake. It is about transformation through carefully drawing lessons from what was and what could be – while remembering responsibility toward suffering.

So next time you think about what you want – what you envy, whom you compare yourself to, and even in small daily choices – ask yourself: how much of this is a wish for experience, and how much is a true, deep wish to be in that situation? And when you feel you made a mistake, when it is unpleasant or you suffer – think: what do you need to experience through this? What are you meant to learn? What do others who contributed to this situation need to learn? What would you need so you could draw the same conclusions without the painful experience?

Ask yourself one simple question: do I want this to experience it, or to be in it?"

- My personal thoughts from a few days ago.
What's your take on this?
author: @GregHinc

Which is in contrast with more linear, methodological and analytical qualities. In brain structures it’s reflected in more expanded or distributed neural firing, compared to more localised concentrated clusters. It’s the difference between focusing on the bigger picture rather than the particular details. Interestingly this also relates to autistic traits if overbalanced in the latter - people who can’t see the wood for the trees, which I think Alex is doing in this moment (not saiying he’s autistic). With respect to metaphysics, or even life in general, it’s best to have balance between the two, in a kind of dialectic. Since if we lose connection with the bigger picture we lose track of the full experience of reality upon which our models should base themselves.

ACIM will still help someone because luckily not understanding this is fine for healing one's mind and world view.  But all spiritualities - Hinduism, forms of Buddhism (not what Buddha himself taught, which refrained from talking about this), various forms of Neo Non-duality and Advaita - don't understand that our being is held in God and sustained in God (which they would agree with), but that is simply the non-dual aspect of our being, not the dual aspect.  The dual aspect is our own choices on this linear plane.  So then what determines whether someone is in good standing with the universe?  It's our level of *communion* with God, or in other words, our relationship with Love.  Separation or unification with God/the Universe/Life/Truth doesn't happen on the existential level as we are always unified on the existential level, it happens on the relational level.  God is deeply intimate while also being deeply impersonal.  Both the Buddhist and Christians were right. comment_text:
Did you know that there are solutions for many if not most of the topics discussed, that can be adapted to all three viewpoints. You explain the same solution from a different perspective, and all of us sudden the different viewpoints become close to irrelevant, except for the persons who receives them. If a christian receives the atheist explanation, for example, or vice versa, they will not accept it. But if they receive the explanation in a form that goes with their belief, it suddenly lands, not knowing that it is based on the same thing.

The most difficult group to adapt to is the traditional christian group, though. Their margins to accept solutions are very narrow because. in their core, those margins come from dogmatic bible interpretations from the past that often don't hold up against the knoweledge we currently have. It is therefore most of the time not the recommended approach for younger generations because of the authoritarive manner in which they are set forth, while most younger people will feel the need to understand it to a certain extent and feel free to apply it. (Even the choice of inviting a christian apologist  underlines the fact that in our time we tend to ask for more than just believing on authority for these types of discussions.

Even so, the more fearful will still be attracted more to religion than to spirituality or atheism, so it's not one size fits all. If you see a big increase in young people going to church, you may be dealing with an important increase in fear among them, apart from the need for meaning in their lives. Many (but not all) spiritual views asks a more active role in the persons own development, which can put off or even scare those who not only feel lost, but overwhelmed as well.

Pure atheism discussing morality and meaning can easily become disingenuous because of the atheist paradigms associated with life, consciousness, evolution and survival. Helping the more fanatic atheist can be difficult because their rejection of what is not yet backed by science, can make the range of psychological tools that are accepted more narrow. Younger generations, and especially Gen Z, are more practical and many don't experience a clear and strict division between science and spirituality. This makes it easier to use a wider range of psychological terms and explanations, as well as elements from buddhism and christianity, for example.

video_title: Atheist vs Christian vs Spiritual Thinker: The Paperclip Problem That Exposes Religion!
comment_text:
God Is Love

I know this may sound unreasonable, but it unfolds when you open your heart, mind, and soul.

Many people wrestle with their own perception of God  sometimes even rejecting the very image they hold. Yet, through the lens of any religion, these are often the same people you’d call faithful and righteous.

“God is love.” Just three simple words, yet they carry all the attributes of who He is. You can reject, abandon, or disagree, but deep within every human being there is a light  a quiet, glittering pull toward goodness. We do good not only because of ethics or social expectations, but because God’s nature lives within us.

When God said, “Let us make man in our own image,” He placed His imprint on us. As His image-bearers, we have free will the ability to choose what to believe and what to walk away from. But nothing can erase that inner spark.

May these words be a blessing to anyone who reads them, and may you encounter God’s nature in the deepest parts of your own being.

comment_text: The paperclip problem is usually about unchecked power and values, but applied to religion it raises deep questions: what happens when belief systems are pursued without balance, context, or compassion? As a philosopher might say, it’s less about which label you wear, atheist, Christian, or spiritualist, and more about how your framework prevents you from turning life into a mindless paperclip factory. A little humor here: if God really cared about paperclips, He’d have probably made them grow on trees by now.
